<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-380-108  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 380 108.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronics  Jan 1990 v63 n1 p70(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>It looks like another good year: the move is on toward openframeworks and interoperability. (1990 outlook for computer-aideddesign and computer-aided engineering systems)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McLeod, Jonah.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The computer-aided design and computer-aided engineering (CAD/CAM)market will grow 17 percent in 1990, with much of the comingdecade's growth fueled by the advent of open CAD/CAE softwareframeworks and improved logic synthesizers and multilevel andstandardized mixed-signal simulators.andP;  Open design frameworks arealready available from Cadence Design Systems and Silicon CompilerSystems.andP;  The new logic synthesizers will significantly reduce thetime for creating an application-specific integrated circuit(ASIC) after simulation and debugging.andP;  Multilevel simulators willhandle ever more complex ICs, and mixed-signal simulators willcomply with the Department of Defense's VHSIC Hardware DescriptionLanguage.andP;  Personal computers are being used more and more forCAD/CAE applications and may challenge workstation dominance ofthe market in the next few years.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Market AnalysisPreview of Coming YearOutlookComputer-aided designComputer-aided engineeringForecasting.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Revenue growth in CAD/CAE hardware and software: 1988-1990.andO;(table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>